{"pageProps":{"note":{"id":"mV9vOl83yp7Z3h5QW4d6s","title":"Lecture 7","vault":{"fsPath":"vault"},"type":"note","desc":"","links":[],"anchors":{"stress-and-strain":{"type":"header","text":"Stress and strain","value":"stress-and-strain","line":8,"column":0},"hooks-law":{"type":"header","text":"Hook's Law","value":"hooks-law","line":10,"column":0},"axial-vs-transverse-force":{"type":"header","text":"Axial vs Transverse force","value":"axial-vs-transverse-force","line":19,"column":0},"compressive-force":{"type":"header","text":"Compressive Force","value":"compressive-force","line":25,"column":0},"strain-gauge":{"type":"header","text":"Strain Gauge","value":"strain-gauge","line":31,"column":0}},"fname":"courses.Semester 5.Sensors.Lecture 7","updated":1631854754508,"created":1631851490710,"parent":"BU8smu6Xa4e3tkB0iVHT9","children":[],"data":{},"contentHash":"70d90476d2733cf0bb7b99a5ac68aa3f","custom":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"lecture-7\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#lecture-7\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Lecture 7</h1>\n<h2 id=\"stress-and-strain\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#stress-and-strain\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Stress and strain</h2>\n<h2 id=\"hooks-law\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#hooks-law\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Hook's Law</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Amount of deformation is proportional to the force applies to any object.</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-09-41-24.png\"></li>\n<li>F = k*(Change in length)</li>\n<li><strong>Note that the force should be small for the relationship to be linear.</strong></li>\n<li>If force greater than the threshold is applied than the relationship is not linear.</li>\n<li>Elstic region corresponds to the range of force where the object will retain its shape.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"axial-vs-transverse-force\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#axial-vs-transverse-force\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Axial vs Transverse force</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>This is called tensile force.</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-09-45-18.png\"></li>\n<li>Transverse strain means along the length of the object at perpendicular angle.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"compressive-force\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#compressive-force\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Compressive Force</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-09-48-42.png\"></li>\n<li><span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>f</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\\\frac{F}{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"mspace newline\"></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span></span> is called stress or pressure.</li>\n<li>Units of young's modulus is same as stress or pressure i.e N/m*2 or Pascal (Pa).</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"strain-gauge\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#strain-gauge\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Strain Gauge</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Sensor for measuring strain</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-10-07-40.png\"></li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-10-10-23.png\"></li>\n<li>Now to calculate change in resistance, we measure the change in current or change in voltage and indirectly find change in resistance.</li>\n<li><span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>f</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\\\frac{Change in R}{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"mspace newline\"></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span></span></span> is very small and adding \"1\" might just lead to nothing.</li>\n<li>To avoid this, we need to set a circuit such that the voltage across the resistor is linearly proportional to <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>f</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\\\frac{Change in R}{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"mspace newline\"></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span></span></span>.</li>\n<li>We need a wheatstone bridge to get the linear proportionality.\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-10-16-43.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Understand the equation formed.</strong></li>\n<li>Bridge circuit for strain measurment\n<ul>\n<li>In the above figure, R4 is the strain gauge whereas others are normal resistors which are all equal.</li>\n<li>In bending strain or a tensile strain, the formula still remains the same becuase in either of the cases, the length of the resistor in the strain gauge will change and hence, resitance will change.</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-10-22-11.png\"></li>\n<li>Final Equation\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-09-17-10-24-07.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Note that the strain will always be positive.</strong> According to the equation the negative value might change as change in voltage (Vo) might be negative if R4 gets too high.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>","noteIndex":{"id":"JEvRiJuvqz4mJX4q7zqJs","title":"Curated Notes","vault":{"fsPath":"vault"},"type":"note","desc":"","links":[],"anchors":{},"fname":"root","updated":1630150480330,"created":1629975412335,"parent":null,"children":["Jq5ki9jf1QLTdc3DYLRW4","3ONxZ3Khb7nFPdLxlV1ib"],"data":{},"contentHash":"f8f9737444f7022ec433cdb6d3c7a764","custom":{"nav_order":0,"permalink":"/"},"body":"\n\r\n\r\nYou have reached the home page of my curated notes. I am a third year student pursuing Computer Science and Engineering at Ahmedabad University.\r\n\r\nFeel free to use this resource to its best potential and reach out to me on [Linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/in/sameep-vani/) and do checkout my [GitHub](https://github.com/Sameep1234)\r\n"},"collectionChildren":null,"customHeadContent":null,"config":{"useFMTitle":true,"useNoteTitleForLink":true,"mermaid":true,"useKatex":true,"dev":{"enablePreviewV2":true},"site":{"siteUrl":"https://sameep1234.github.io","assetsPrefix":"/notes","copyAssets":true,"siteHierarchies":["root"],"siteRootDir":"docs","usePrettyRefs":true,"title":"Sameep","description":"Personal knowledge space","duplicateNoteBehavior":{"action":"useVault","payload":["vault"]},"author":"Sameep","logo":"vault/logo.gif","ga_tracking":"G-VZ67P3SVZE","siteLastModified":true,"gh_edit_branch":"main","usePrettyLinks":true,"siteNotesDir":"notes","siteF